151→src/blog/2024/view-transition-at-rule.md:8:  description: Updates to MPA view transitions and the at-rule
152→src/blog/2024/view-transition-at-rule.md:13:Last year [I wrote](https://tylergaw.com/blog/view-transitions-first-experiments-mpa/) about [MPA view transitions](https://tylergaw.com/blog/complex-mpa-view-transitions/). Since then, the spec has been expanded and browser support has improved slightly.
153→src/blog/2024/view-transition-at-rule.md:15:## The @view-transition at-rule
154→src/blog/2024/view-transition-at-rule.md:17:[`@view-transitions`](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/CSS/@view-transition) is a new transitions-related at-rule. For multi-page transitions it’s required. This is a breaking change to existing multi-page transitions. Any site, include this one, that had existing multi-page transitions no longer work without `@view-transition`.
155→src/blog/2024/view-transition-at-rule.md:19:In section 2.1.1. “Activation” of [CSS View Transitions Module Level 2](https://www.w3.org/TR/css-view-transitions-2/#activating-cross-document-view-transition) (emphasis added)
156→src/blog/2024/view-transition-at-rule.md:21:> In cross-document view transition, what triggers a view transition is a navigation between two documents, as long as the following conditions are met:
157→src/blog/2024/view-transition-at-rule.md:27:> - **both documents opted in to cross-document view transitions, using the @view-transition rule.**
158→src/blog/2024/view-transition-at-rule.md:32:@view-transition {
159→src/blog/2024/view-transition-at-rule.md:37:Right now, the value of `navigation` can be `auto` or `none`. Unclear if the possible values will change in the future, but it’s possible. The spec mentions that `@view-transition` can be nested inside other at-rules like `@media` or `@supports`. I haven’t tried this yet, but that could be a good way to only enable or disable transitions under certain conditions. For example, we could default to not having transitions and only enable them if the user has not opted for reduced-motion:
160→src/blog/2024/view-transition-at-rule.md:41:@view-transition {
161→src/blog/2024/view-transition-at-rule.md:46:  @view-transition {
162→src/blog/2024/view-transition-at-rule.md:52:This is likely preferable to putting a bunch of view transition pseudo selectors in `@media (prefers-reduced-motion: no-preference)` blocks like I’m [currently doing](https://tylergaw.com/blog/complex-mpa-view-transitions/).
163→src/blog/2024/view-transition-at-rule.md:56:Previously, two feature flags were required in Chrome/Arc to enable multi-page transitions. `chrome://flags#view-transition` and `chrome://flags#view-transition-on-navigation`. <s>It seems `view-transition` has been removed. I don’t have details on why or when, but it doesn’t show up anymore.</s> It’s because the spec was still in progress at the time. `view-transition-on-navigation` now defaults to being on, so if you’re in Chrome, transitions should just work.
164→src/blog/2024/view-transition-at-rule.md:58:Overall support is still limited. In my testing these still only work in Chrome and Arc. No Firefox or Safari. I did get [an issue](https://github.com/tylergaw/mpa-view-transitions-sandbox/issues/2) about my transitions demos being broken that said transitions work in Safari Tech Preview 18, but I haven’t tested there yet.
165→src/blog/2024/view-transition-at-rule.md:60:Great to see these features moving forward. I’m keeping the [sandbox](https://github.com/tylergaw/mpa-view-transitions-sandbox) up to date. Thanks to folks that emailed and created an issue there about things being broken. Keep those coming.

